{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595492"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:04:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:04:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15361"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15361"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.03,0.03,0.17,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69844"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8052"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55300"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"},{"type":"tags","id":"10886"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19554"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69844"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENucleoside analogues are a key treatment option for chronic hepatitis B infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about nucleoside analogue therapy for hepatitis B is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Entecavir and tenofovir are first-line treatment options","Treatment can be stopped once liver enzymes normalize","The drugs work by stimulating the immune response","Viral RNA polymerase is the primary drug target","The drugs prevent viral protein synthesis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic hepatitis B infection can be treated with nucleoside analogues. \u003Cstrong\u003EEntecavir and tenofovir\u003C/strong\u003E are the preferred first-line agents due to their high potency and high barrier to resistance. These medications work by directly inhibiting viral DNA polymerase, thereby blocking viral replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreatment can be stopped once liver enzymes normalize\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - nucleoside analogue therapy typically requires long-term or indefinite treatment to maintain viral suppression. The drugs do not primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulating the immune response\u003C/strong\u003E. The target is viral DNA polymerase, not \u003Cstrong\u003Eviral RNA polymerase\u003C/strong\u003E. While the drugs inhibit viral replication, they do not directly \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevent viral protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Nucleoside analogues directly inhibit hepatitis B viral replication by blocking viral DNA polymerase","Entecavir and tenofovir are first-line nucleoside analogue treatments for chronic hepatitis B infection","Nucleoside analogue therapy for hepatitis B typically requires long-term or indefinite treatment"],"references":["Mehta P, Grant LM, Reddivari AKR. Viral Hepatitis. 2024 Mar 10. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32119436","Lok AS, Pawlotsky JM. Viral hepatitis at a crossroad. Gastroenterology. 2012 May;142(6):1261-3. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2012.03.007. PMID: 22537431","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Scienc","Song JE, Kim DY. Diagnosis of hepatitis B. Ann Transl Med. 2016 Sep;4(18):338. doi: 10.21037/atm.2016.09.11. PMID: 27761442; PMCID: PMC5066055"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55300"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15361"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55300"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T20:37:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T20:42:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8052"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69844"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":